^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Bidding was pretty vanilla. Let's talk about the play. First the opening lead. I advocate 4th best in general, which is what Evar led. However, it is also usually not right to lead a suit the opponents have bid. Some might say clubs might not be a real suit, since you can open 1C with a 3 card suit. However, it turns out that about 85% of the time, opener has at least 4 clubs, so it is usually a real suit. In this case, I probably would pick my better major and lead a spade with Evar's hand.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, let us look at it from Lisa's perspective. Once Deb wins the A, Lisa is pretty sure she has 2 club tricks, because Deb would have played the Q if she had AQ and Evar must have the Queen. Next when Deb leads back a diamond, and it wins Lisa is sure of 3 diamond tricks. That is 5 tricks. And there are 2 sure spades and 1 sure heart, so that is 8 tricks for sure. |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The question now is, how best to play the hearts for an extra trick. Probably the best line is to cash the Ace of hearts first and then lead low towards the @hQ10. Hopefully, an honor will pop up from West, but if it doesn't, then you probably should play the 10. Even if that fails, when you get back to your hand, you can play low towards the Queen. |
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Basically, you are likely to take at least 2 heart tricks, and on good days, 3, as in this hand. Actually, as it turns out, you can make 4 if you play the hearts as suggested, however making 3 is still a good result.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


