PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|There are plusses and minuses to playing Puppet Stayman over 1N. Puppet Stayman is a way to discover whether the NT opener has a 4 card major or a 5 card major. Without going into the gory details, basically, the way it works is over 2C, the NT opener only bids a major if they have 5 cards in it. If they have a 4 card major they bid 2D. If they have no 4 card major they bid 2NT.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The advantage is you can still open 1N with 5 card major, and find 5-3 fits. The disadvantage is 1) you can't play "garbage Stayman", where you are planning to pass whatever the NT bidder responds with. The other disadvantage is, for those who play 2N as a diamond transfer, you can no longer play that. |
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Anther problem is puppet Stayman is fairly complicated. However, none of these disadvantages are overwhelming, so if you want to play puppet, that would be fine. I mostly play weak NT, so the problem does not exist for me. However, when I play strong NT, I play 4 suit transfers, including 2N as diamond transfer, so I cannot play puppet Stayman.|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My feeling is that most of the time, you do just as well in 3N as in a 5-3 major fit, so I don't consider it a big loss not to play puppet.|
